{"parse":{"title":"Gloria Wekker","pageid":49387044,"revid":858233297,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\"><span class=\"fn\">Gloria Wekker</span></th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:GloriaWekker2016.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"GloriaWekker2016.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/GloriaWekker2016.jpg/220px-GloriaWekker2016.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/GloriaWekker2016.jpg/330px-GloriaWekker2016.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/GloriaWekker2016.jpg/440px-GloriaWekker2016.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"814\" data-file-height=\"611\" /></a><div>Wekker (2016)</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Born</th><td>\n<span style=\"display:none\"> (<span class=\"bday\">1950-06-13</span>) </span>June 13, 1950<span class=\"noprint ForceAgeToShow\"> (age&#160;68)</span><br /><span class=\"birthplace\"><a href=\"/wiki/Paramaribo\" title=\"Paramaribo\">Paramaribo</a>, Suriname</span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Nationality</th><td class=\"category\">\nSurinamese / Dutch</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Occupation</th><td class=\"role\">\neducator, writer</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Years&#160;active</th><td>\n1981&#8211;present</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Known&#160;for</th><td>\nAfro-Caribbean and gender studies</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><span style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Notable work</span></th><td>\n<i>The Politics of Passion</i></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Gloria Daisy Wekker</b> (born June 13, 1950) is an <a href=\"/wiki/Afro-Surinamese\" title=\"Afro-Surinamese\">Afro-Surinamese</a> Dutch educator and writer who has focused on gender studies and sexuality in the Afro-Caribbean region and diaspora. She was the winner of the Ruth Benedict Prize from the <a href=\"/wiki/American_Anthropological_Association\" title=\"American Anthropological Association\">American Anthropological Association</a> in 2007.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Biography\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Biography</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Selected_works\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Selected works</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Sources\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Sources</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Biography\">Biography</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Gloria_Wekker&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Biography\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Gloria Wekker was born in 1950 in <a href=\"/wiki/Paramaribo\" title=\"Paramaribo\">Paramaribo</a>, Suriname.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Surinam_Stars_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Surinam_Stars-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> She moved to <a href=\"/wiki/Amsterdam\" title=\"Amsterdam\">Amsterdam</a> in the 1970s and became active in the Afro-European Women\u2019s Movement.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Encyclopedia_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Encyclopedia-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Wekker earned a master's degree in <a href=\"/wiki/Cultural_anthropology\" title=\"Cultural anthropology\">cultural anthropology</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-Surinam_Stars_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Surinam_Stars-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> from the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Amsterdam\" title=\"University of Amsterdam\">University of Amsterdam</a> in 1981 and began her career working in various governmental agencies in Amsterdam, such as the Ministry of Health, Welfare and Culture on Ethnic Minorities' Affairs and the Ministry of Social Affairs and Employment. In 1984, she became a founding member of \"Sister Outsider\", an Amsterdam-based, literary circle for lesbian black women named after the work by <a href=\"/wiki/Audre_Lorde\" title=\"Audre Lorde\">Audre Lorde</a>. In 1987, she served as a Policy Associate in the Office for the Coordination of Ethnic Minorities' Affairs.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Encyclopedia_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Encyclopedia-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 1992, Wekker earned her doctorate at the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_California,_Los_Angeles\" title=\"University of California, Los Angeles\">University of California, Los Angeles</a> with a thesis on the sexuality and subjectivity of Afro-Surinamese women. In 2001, she was appointed to the Aletta-chair of the Department of Women's Studies at the <a href=\"/wiki/Utrecht_University\" title=\"Utrecht University\">Utrecht University</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Surinam_Stars_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Surinam_Stars-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Dialogo_Global_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Dialogo_Global-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-UWI_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-UWI-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Her work focuses on the intersections of <a href=\"/wiki/Colonialism\" title=\"Colonialism\">colonialism</a>, racism, <a href=\"/wiki/White_privilege\" title=\"White privilege\">white privilege</a>, feminist theory, lesbian theory and women in the Caribbean.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Duke_Press_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Duke_Press-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBatra2011155_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBatra2011155-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Her work has earned her the title of \"Holland\u2019s <a href=\"/wiki/Angela_Davis\" title=\"Angela Davis\">Angela Davis</a>\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Neilson,_2014_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Neilson,_2014-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> as she has forced the Dutch to examine their alleged ingrained stereotypes and attitudes towards racism and patriarchy.<sup id=\"cite_ref-De_Wereld_Morgen_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-De_Wereld_Morgen-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> She has led debate which questioned the racist nature of such iconic images in Dutch tradition as <a href=\"/wiki/Santa\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Santa\">Sinterklaas</a> (Santa Clause)'s helpers as <a href=\"/wiki/Blackface\" title=\"Blackface\">blackface</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Golliwogs\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Golliwogs\">golliwogs</a> known as <i>Zwarte Piet</i> (Black Pete),<sup id=\"cite_ref-Neilson,_2014_7-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Neilson,_2014-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-ten_Broeke,_2014_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ten_Broeke,_2014-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> as well as the imagery of what constitutes beauty.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Julen,_2013_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Julen,_2013-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Wekker was nominated in 2004 for the Dutch Scientific Research Council's \"Triomfprijs\" (Triumph prize).<sup id=\"cite_ref-Encyclopedia_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Encyclopedia-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> In 2006, her book <i>The Politics of Passion: Women's Sexual Culture in the Afro-Surinamese Diaspora</i> won critical praise<sup id=\"cite_ref-review_The_Politics_of_Passion_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-review_The_Politics_of_Passion-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> and was awarded with the 2007 Ruth Benedict Prize from the American Anthropological Association.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Dialogo_Global_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Dialogo_Global-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Utrecht_12-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Utrecht-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> In 2011, she began a sabbatical to work at the Netherlands Institute for Advanced Studies on a research project,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Encyclopedia_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Encyclopedia-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> which resulted in the publication in 2016 of <i>White Innocence: Paradoxes of Colonialism and Race</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Duke_Press_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Duke_Press-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Because of her work with both sociology and policy, Wekker has been named as part of an international committee which was appointed at the University of Amsterdam in 2015 to increase diversity at the university.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Science_Guide_13-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Science_Guide-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Selected_works\">Selected works</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Gloria_Wekker&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Selected works\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Wekker, Gloria (1986). <i>Oog in oog: over het werk van Audre Lorde</i> (in Dutch). Utrecht, The Netherlands: Savannah Bay.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Oog+in+oog%3A+over+het+werk+van+Audre+Lorde&amp;rft.place=Utrecht%2C+The+Netherlands&amp;rft.pub=Savannah+Bay&amp;rft.date=1986&amp;rft.aulast=Wekker&amp;rft.aufirst=Gloria&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGloria+Wekker\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Wekker, Gloria; Wekker, Herman (1990). <i><span></span>'Coming in from the cold': linguistic and socio-cultural aspects of the translation of Black English Vernacular literary texts into Surinamese Dutch</i> (in Dutch). Leiden, The Netherlands: Vakgroep Engels.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=%27Coming+in+from+the+cold%27%3A+linguistic+and+socio-cultural+aspects+of+the+translation+of+Black+English+Vernacular+literary+texts+into+Surinamese+Dutch&amp;rft.place=Leiden%2C+The+Netherlands&amp;rft.pub=Vakgroep+Engels&amp;rft.date=1990&amp;rft.aulast=Wekker&amp;rft.aufirst=Gloria&amp;rft.au=Wekker%2C+Herman&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGloria+Wekker\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation thesis\">Wekker, Gloria (1992). <i>\"I am gold money\": (I pass through all hands, but I do not lose my value): the construction of selves, gender and sexualities in a female working class, Afro-Surinamese setting</i> (Ph.D.). University of California, Los Angeles.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Adissertation&amp;rft.title=%22I+am+gold+money%22%3A+%28I+pass+through+all+hands%2C+but+I+do+not+lose+my+value%29%3A+the+construction+of+selves%2C+gender+and+sexualities+in+a+female+working+class%2C+Afro-Surinamese+setting&amp;rft.inst=University+of+California%2C+Los+Angeles&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.aulast=Wekker&amp;rft.aufirst=Gloria&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGloria+Wekker\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Wekker, Gloria (1994). <i>Ik ben een gouden munt, ik ga door vele handen, maar verlies mijn waarde niet: subjectiviteit en seksualiteit van Creoolse volksklasse vrouwen in Paramaribo</i> (in Dutch). Amsterdam, The Netherlands: VITA.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Ik+ben+een+gouden+munt%2C+ik+ga+door+vele+handen%2C+maar+verlies+mijn+waarde+niet%3A+subjectiviteit+en+seksualiteit+van+Creoolse+volksklasse+vrouwen+in+Paramaribo&amp;rft.place=Amsterdam%2C+The+Netherlands&amp;rft.pub=VITA&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.aulast=Wekker&amp;rft.aufirst=Gloria&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGloria+Wekker\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation journal\">Wekker, Gloria (1997). \"One finger does not drink okra soup: Afro-Surinamese women and critical agency\". <i>Feminist genealogies, colonial legacies, democratic futures</i>. New York, NY: Routledge: 330&#8211;352.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Feminist+genealogies%2C+colonial+legacies%2C+democratic+futures&amp;rft.atitle=One+finger+does+not+drink+okra+soup%3A+Afro-Surinamese+women+and+critical+agency&amp;rft.pages=330-352&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft.aulast=Wekker&amp;rft.aufirst=Gloria&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGloria+Wekker\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation journal\">Wekker, Gloria (1998). \"Thamyris\". <i>Feminist genealogies, colonial legacies, democratic futures</i>. Leiden, The Netherlands: Brill Publishers. <b>5</b> (1): 105&#8211;129.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Feminist+genealogies%2C+colonial+legacies%2C+democratic+futures&amp;rft.atitle=Thamyris&amp;rft.volume=5&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=105-129&amp;rft.date=1998&amp;rft.aulast=Wekker&amp;rft.aufirst=Gloria&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGloria+Wekker\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Wekker, Gloria (2001). \"Mati-ism and black lesbianism: two idealtypical expressions of female homosexuality in black communities of the diaspora\".  In Constantine-Simms, Delroy. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=57SGAAAAIAAJ\"><i>The Greatest Taboo: Homosexuality in Black Communities</i></a>. Los Angeles, California: Alyson Books. pp.&#160;149&#8211;162. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-55583-564-4\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-1-55583-564-4\">978-1-55583-564-4</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Mati-ism+and+black+lesbianism%3A+two+idealtypical+expressions+of+female+homosexuality+in+black+communities+of+the+diaspora&amp;rft.btitle=The+Greatest+Taboo%3A+Homosexuality+in+Black+Communities&amp;rft.place=Los+Angeles%2C+California&amp;rft.pages=149-162&amp;rft.pub=Alyson+Books&amp;rft.date=2001&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-55583-564-4&amp;rft.aulast=Wekker&amp;rft.aufirst=Gloria&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D57SGAAAAIAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGloria+Wekker\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Wekker, Gloria (2002). <i>Nesten bouwen op een winderige plek&#160;: denken over gender en etniciteit in Nederland</i> (in Dutch). Utrecht, The Netherlands: Universiteit Utrecht, Faculteit der Letteren. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-907-6-91223-3\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-907-6-91223-3\">978-907-6-91223-3</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft